ways ask first, even if CI passes.\n- Prefer safe alternatives (`git revert`, new commits, temp branches).\n- If history rewrite seems necessary, explain and ask first.\n- Add `Co-Authored-By: chatgpt-codex-connector[bot] <199175422+chatgpt-codex-connector[bot]@users.noreply.github.com>` to commits by default, unless explicitly asked not to.\n\n## Using GitHub\n\nFor questions about GitHub, use the `gh` tool and `/octocat` skill.\nAlways run `gh` commands with escalated permissions; sandboxed `gh` calls fail in this environment because network access is restricted there.\nNever mention Codex in PR descriptions, PR comments, or issue comments unless asked explicitly.\nDo not include a \"Test plan\" section in PR descriptions.\n\n## Coding Standards\n\n### PHP Coding Standards\n\nWhen working with Laravel/PHP projects, always use the `php-guidelines-from-spatie` skill.\n\n## Reviewing external feedback\n\n- ALWAYS load the `superpowers:receiving-code-review` skill upon receiving review feedback (PR comments, agent reviews). The skill enforces technical rigor and verification over performative agreement.\n- When acting on PR review comments (from bots or humans), independently verify factual claims before applying fixes — especially version numbers, library existence, API behavior, and deprecation status.\n- If a claim falls outside your knowledge cutoff, use WebSearch or check local evidence (installed packages, lock files, docker images) before trusting it.\n- Use `pr-review-fetcher` agent to fetch Pull Review reviews and comments.\n\n## Production safety\n\n- Assume production impact unless stated otherwise.\n- Call out risk when touching auth, billing, data, APIs, or build systems.\n- Prefer small, reversible changes; avoid silent breaking behavior.\n\n## Self improvement\n\n- Continuously improve agent workflows.\n- When a repeated correction or better approach is found you're encouraged to codify your new found knowledge and learnings by modifying your section of